english:
  title: Epitaph for the Tomb of Duke Shin Sukju, Lord of Golyeong, a Man of Literary Achievement and Loyalty
  author: Lee Seung-so
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I observe that when the world declines, Heaven, in its wisdom to restore it, sends forth sage rulers and virtuous ministers who work together to stabilize an age and establish great governance. Thus when the Shang fell into decay, there arose Fu Shuo to aid the High King, achieving a renaissance. When the Zhou declined, there came Fang Shu to serve King Xuan, restoring former glory. Yet comparing these to our time: Fu Shuo possessed the talents of a minister but left no martial legacy, while Fang Shu achieved military victories but showed no gifts for statecraft. How can they be compared to our Lord Munching—one whose heaven-given talents were complete, whose fortune matched his ability, who served the sage ruler as both strategist and commander, who went forth as general and returned as premier, who steadied the tottering realm and secured it as firmly as Mount Tai? Since our Eastern Kingdom was established, there has been but one minister whose virtue and service reached such heights. In the eleventh year of Seonghwa, in the sixth month, on the day mujo, he passed away at his residence from illness. When news reached the throne, the sovereign grieved as one who had lost both hands. He ceased dining and suspended court, sent his closest counselors to offer condolences, and bestowed generous gifts. Thus the court lost its mainstay, the scholarly world its exemplar, the bureaucracy lost one to whom it could turn for guidance, and the common people lost one to whom they could look for support. Even children and soldiers wept without ceasing. His students, former subordinates, relatives, and colleagues gathered at his coffin daily in endless procession—proof that his esteem among men came not from eloquence or appearance alone, but from something far deeper.

    On the twenty-sixth day of the ninth month, he was buried on an east-facing slope in Songsan of Yangju. From the day of his passing until his interment, all expenses were borne by the crown. After the burial, his successor brought me his life account and asked me to compose this epitaph, saying, "You spent the longest years in the company of my father—will you not immortalize him in stone?" I could not refuse.

    His given name was Sukju, his courtesy name Beom-ong, and his pseudonym Huixeon-dang. He was of the Golyeong Shin clan. His ancestors were minor officials in their native county, until one named Seongyong passed the examination and rose to the rank of Inspector of the Military Equipage Bureau. Four generations later came Deok-rin, who served as Chief of Ceremonial Rites and became his great-grandfather. This ancestor excelled in seal script, running script, and clerical script. He fathered Poching, who became a Eunuch of the Public Works Ministry and served as his grandfather. Poching's son was Jang, who became Left Deputy Minister of Public Works—he became our subject's father, and long held the position of Minister of Civil Examination and became the scholarly exemplar of his generation. From the family of the Chief onwards, all received honors and ranks through our subject's great service. His mother was of the Jeong clan, daughter of the Governor of Seongju.

    He was born in the sixth month on the day jeong-yu of the year byeong-yu in the Yongle era. From childhood he showed keen intelligence and refined bearing; those who saw him recognized he would become a great vessel. As he matured, he devoted himself to learning and studied all books under heaven. From this deep cultivation emerged poetry and prose of great breadth and power, uncontaminated by vulgarity, which became the model for his generation.

    In the year mu-o, he first rose to the rank of Jinsa through poetry and prose examinations, achieving first place in both preliminary and advanced trials, and passing the civil service examination. The following autumn, King Sejong personally administered the palace examination, and our subject placed third. He was first appointed as a junior official in the Bureau of Agriculture. When the Ministry of Civil Service assigned him to oversee a ritual, a clerk failed to deliver the notice and he was impeached. Hearing the clerk was elderly and fearing the man's dismissal, he took responsibility himself—revealing himself as both generous and magnanimous.

    He was selected for the Hall of Worthies as Vice-Draftsman. Each morning after greeting his superior, he would retreat to the Library to read books he had not yet seen, studying without cease. When taking night duty shifts, he would read through the night. One evening, past midnight, King Sejong sent a young eunuch to observe him—the subject sat upright reading. The king sent another observer at the fourth watch—the same scene. The king immediately bestowed robes upon him as reward.

    In the year im-sul, he was promoted to Assistant Director of the Military Training Bureau. Since Japan valued literature and sent envoys seeking worthy scribes, the court wished to send an ambassador. All candidates declined due to fear of the sea voyage, so he was selected. Having just recovered from prolonged illness, his brothers and relatives urged him not to go, saying his weakened condition made such a journey impossible. He replied, "A servant of the state must treat hard and easy with equal spirit—I cannot put my own comfort first." At his audience, King Sejong asked if he was well enough to travel. He answered, "My health is restored—I dare not refuse."

    Upon arrival, word of his talents spread, and people came requesting his poetry. His brush never ceased, and though he seemed to write effortlessly, every line astounded readers—his verses are still recited today. Each time envoys returned, they asked about his welfare.

    While at sea, he could read the weather to predict storms, skills even veteran sailors could not match. Our country had agreed with Tsushima to send a fixed number of ships annually, but the island lord, influenced by advisors, refused. On his return journey, stopping at the island, he told the lord, "Though such matters are not for envoys to discuss, I have puzzled over this. If a fixed quota is established, written authorization must be issued before ships reach our shore—thus authority lies with you, and your profit is great. Without fixed quotas, anyone travels freely—what need would they have of your services? The advantage is clear to even the unwise." The lord understood and agreed to the arrangement.

    Arriving near our coast, they encountered a typhoon and could not land. The crew panicked, but he remained composed, saying, "A true gentleman should travel far to broaden his mind. We have crossed the sea and seen the land of sunrise—what a spectacle! If this wind carries us to China, we might see the splendor of civilization itself—would that not be fortune?" He noticed a Korean woman among the refugees, pregnant and in labor, and ordered her placed on the ship. The crew protested that an expectant woman brought bad fortune and should be cast into the sea to prevent disaster. He refused, saying, "To kill for one's own safety offends virtue—I cannot do it." Soon after, the wind calmed.

    King Sejong, noting that other lands had scripts for their languages but our kingdom lacked one, created twenty-eight letters called Hunminjeongeum and established a bureau to formulate it. Our subject alone had access to the inner court, where he personally received the royal instruction and helped establish the five tones' clarity and obscurity, and the system of consonants and vowels. Where others merely preserved what was given, he created anew.

    When the king wished to transliterate Chinese sounds using these letters, and heard that the scholar Hwang Chan had been exiled to Liaodong for an offense, he sent our subject to question him there. Whatever the scholar explained, our subject grasped instantly without error. Chan greatly admired him, and over thirteen journeys to Liaodong, he became increasingly trusted.

    In autumn of the year jeong-myo, he passed the special examination at the fourth rank and was promoted to Lecturer in the Hall of Worthies. In spring of gyeong-o, when the envoy Ni Qian arrived with imperial edicts, King Sejong had our subject attend him. Through nightly dialogues on classical learning and poetry, the envoys recognized him as the great master of the Eastern lands. When one envoy composed "A Snowy Clearing from a Tower," our subject matched his verses with such brilliance that the envoy wrote upon leaving, "Your words have graced the immortal stages of Qu and Song, and your fame spreads through the court." Such was their respect.

    Seeing his gifts for statecraft, the king appointed him Censor-in-Chief. He repeatedly submitted memorials, speaking truth without fear, embodying the ancient spirit of remonstrance. Soon he was promoted to Vice-Censor. In the year sin-mi, he entered the Hall of Worthies again as Chief Lecturer. In autumn of im-sin, when the future King Sejo departed as envoy to China, the court recommended our subject as scribe. Though powerful factions held power and feared the journey, he traveled ten thousand li safeguarding the young prince, and they returned successfully.

    In spring of gye-yu, he became Commander of the Imperial Guard and concurrently Minister of War. He rose through the ranks to become Vice-Minister and then Minister of the Chancellery. In winter, when King Sejo stabilized the realm, though our subject was away, having participated in secret councils, he received the title of Merit Subject for Loyalty and Cooperation in Restoration, with the royal inscription: "Ten thousand li traveled together, sworn to die for the state." Soon after, he was made Chief Minister of the Chancellery.

    In summer of eul-hae, King Sejo ascended the throne. He frequently summoned our subject to his private chambers for counsel. Drawing on ancient and modern examples, our subject demonstrated both benefits and harms, and the king approved, saying, "If I had one more minister like you, what could I fear?" He was given the title of Merit Subject for Virtuous Cooperation and promoted through multiple ranks to become Chancellor of the Hall of Worthies and Lord of Golyeong. After presenting credentials at the Ming court, he received imperial appointments and returned with grants of land and servants.

    In spring of byeong-ja, promoted to Minister of War, he memorialized, "Our kingdom faces enemies on three sides, and the sea pirates are especially fierce—losing this moment would endanger the south." The king replied, "You have traveled and know their true condition; I entrust all diplomatic matters to you." That summer, when the cases of Seongsangmun and others arose, hundreds were implicated and imprisoned. The king ordered him to judge fairly. Through careful investigation, many were spared. He rose to Chief of the State Council while retaining his position as Minister of War, then became Right State Counselor and Rector of the National Academy, holding the supreme position in scholarly matters.

    In autumn of jeong-chuk, he became Left State Counselor, and that winter rose to Right Minister of State. In summer of gi-myo, citing prolonged rains, he submitted his resignation. The royal reply refused him, stating, "You and I share in Heaven's transforming work—if you retreat, how can I advance?" That winter he rose to Left Minister of State.

    Earlier, when the northern peoples frequently invaded, there was division in court about whether to campaign. He alone argued for military action with sound strategy. The king agreed, saying, "Your words match my thoughts precisely." In autumn of gyeong-sin, he was appointed Inspector-General of Kangwon and Hamgyeong provinces and sent to suppress the invaders. Dividing his forces into multiple columns that advanced together, he penetrated deep into their strongholds, destroyed their camps, and returned victorious. The enemy attacked by night, the camp was in turmoil, but he lay calmly in his quarters, composing verses with his staff:

    "On the barren heights, frost descends on the cold frontier,
    Iron cavalry sweeps a hundred leagues through night.
    The battle rages yet as dawn approaches—
    Lying down, I watch the stars in their splendor."

    Seeing his composure, the troops remained steadfast. His strategic commands caused both bold and timid soldiers to fight with unified spirit, and his adaptive tactics prevented the enemy from succeeding. Even ancient generals could not surpass this. Returning in triumph, the king's rewards were without measure.

    In the year im-o, he rose to the position of Chief of State Council. In the year gap-sin, citing his full service, he requested retirement and was granted the title of Lord of Golyeong. In the year jeong-hae, he concurrently served as Minister of Rites. In autumn of mu-ja, when King Sejo passed away and King Seongjong ascended, by the late king's wishes, he was commanded into the Chancellery to participate in all matters. He devoted himself to assisting and illuminating governance. That winter, when Southern Yi's rebellion was quelled, he received the title of Merit Subject for Protecting and Assisting in Restoration.

    That winter of gi-chuk, King Seongjong also passed away, leaving both court and realm in confusion. He alone proposed to the Queen Regent that the succession should be quickly established to calm the people. The queen regent ordered the young king to receive the mandate. In summer of sin-myo, he received the title of Merit Subject for Pure Sincerity, Luminous Wisdom, Economical Governance, and Civilizing Enhancement, and was given the secret seal to authorize his authority and prevent turmoil.

    That winter, he was again appointed Chief Minister, but petitioned for retirement. The Queen Regent's edict stated, "King Sejo called you another Wei Zheng—have you forgotten? Why this sudden retreat?" The king issued his own decree, "I have heard that my late father told my predecessor, 'With Sukju, I established the great laws—in your time, both shall enjoy great peace.' Now I am but a child—how can you refuse?" In summer of im-jin, citing age and illness, he again submitted a memorial presenting urgent state concerns. The king did not allow his retirement and ordered his words copied for personal reflection.

    He was commanded to oversee compilation of the records of Kings Sejo and Seongjong. When completed, a banquet was held in his honor, and he received robes and horses as gifts. In spring of gap-o, citing natural calamities, he again sought retirement. The royal response, written in his own hand, consoled and urged him to continue.

    In spring of eul-mi, the king sent an official with palace wine and horses, writing, "Learning of the envoy's words, I now understand how deep the treachery runs. When you first reported the alarm, you proposed the finest strategy, saving the nation from regret. I rejoice in this greatly."

    Earlier, when the Jurchen of Jianzhou threatened invasion, all believed it mere posturing. He alone proposed sending reinforcements to guard strategic positions, and the attackers were prevented from succeeding. When King Sejo first commanded him to compile the Comprehensive Record of the Eastern Kingdom but state business prevented completion, the king now ordered selected scholars to work at his residence under his direction. The compilation was completed, and he was granted official stipends.

    King Sejo also ordered revision of the Five Rites. Though scholars debated for three reigns without resolution, the king commanded him to edit and finalize it. Weighing ancient and modern sources, considering both propriety and human feeling, he created an imperishable canon. Proficient in the languages of many lands, he personally translated them, making learning accessible without teachers. He recorded the mountains and strategic passes of Japan and Jurched territories in maps for military planners. He compiled a comprehensive record of Eastern nations including their rulers, tribal chiefs, military strength, territories, customs, ships' routes, and our reception protocols—so that officials need not rely on local guides, seeing clearly what they might have walked themselves.

    When he fell gravely ill, the king sent his personal physicians and attendants, providing imperial medicines and kitchen preparations. When critical, the king sent officials to inquire of his final wishes. He counseled that with the nation at peace, northern defenses had grown negligible and must be urgently strengthened. His final testament commanded simple burial, with books as grave goods, without Buddhist rites.

    His nature was luminous and profound; his moral character deep as an abyss. His open-mindedness could embrace all; his bold talent could accomplish much. In learning, he transcended textual commentary to pursue the intent of sages. In writing, he abandoned empty ornament to follow the ancient masters. In daily conduct, he was warm and accessible while maintaining propriety; in handling affairs, he was expansive with room to spare while holding to principle. In argument, he was flexible without obstruction, yet always preserved the essential and did not cavil at details.

    When King Sejo reformed all governance, though our subject long held key positions, he managed affairs through gentle guidance, never selling his words to win fame. The king increasingly esteemed him. During troubled times, when the realm grew uncertain, he and one or two great ministers worked with one heart to support the throne and stabilize the age, exhausting their sincerity for nearly two decades. Military and state affairs accumulated before him; responding left and right, his judgments flowed like water. He seemed careless, yet when his actions took effect, all proved perfectly appropriate. When court debates divided opinion into factions, he drew on precedent and current circumstances to arrive at the just middle way, and all acquiesced.

    When he led the Royal Lectures, he would repeatedly expound matters touching the king's virtue or affecting current governance, seeking to inspire understanding. He would say, "The source of civilization lies in honoring schools," persuading the king to visit the National Academy to revere the ancient sages and discuss difficult texts. He would say, "The foundation of nurturing the people lies in promoting agriculture and sericulture," assisting the king in performing the imperial plowing ceremony and personally sacrificing to the agricultural deity. Retiring, he and the three great ministers would take the plow and till the fields themselves. For matters left incomplete by former reigns, he largely brought them to realization.

    Presiding over fourteen civil service examinations, he identified talent most abundantly—many rose to minister rank. This was because his judgment was so clear that none could deceive him with favoritism. For decades managing the Ministry of Rites, he took serving the great and befriending neighbors as his charge, polishing all official dispatches with such grace that both sides maintained perfect courtesy, giving generously while receiving sparingly, always gaining their goodwill. He often said, "In human relations, though it seems easy, it is truly difficult. Only sincere devotion can move others. The trust of the Central Harmony reaches even pigs and fish—how much more people?"

    When the king received envoys from all quarters, he commanded our subject to convey the royal intent. His bearing was dignified, and all guests revered him. He treated friends with integrity, raising capable men according to their talents. He would quote Ouyang Xiu: "Even the foolish can be employed, even the weak can be employed," saying that people possess no fixed quality—all depends on how they are used. He treated relatives with kindness, even distant kinfolk as dear as children, personally nursing them in sickness and orphans to maturity.

    Alas! Though he long held power and favor, he preserved his achievements. Though he repeatedly grasped authority, he did not diminish his reputation. His name moved China, his authority impressed the foreign peoples, his service encompassed an age, yet no jealous words arose against him. This was because his learning and integrity had reached their perfection, and his deeds showed such towering grandeur as a result. King Sejo once said, "As Duke Huan had Guan Zhong, as the Han founder had Zhang Liang, as Tang Taizong had Wei Zheng—so do I have Sukju. Their meeting was surely Heaven's gift, not human effort."

    He married the daughter of Minister Yun Gyeong-yeon and had eight sons and one daughter. His eldest son Ju became Official of the Ritual Gate; his second son Myeon became Inspector of Hamgyeong; both predeceased him. His third son Chan became Inspector of Hwanghae; his fourth son Jeong became Deputy Minister of Civil Service, passing the examination in the year byeong-sul, and his fifth son Jun became Deputy Minister of War, achieving first place in the year gyeong-in—both Jeong and Jun received the title of Merit Subject for Assistance. His sixth son Bo became Military Commander; his seventh son Hyeong became Supervisor of Court Provisions, passing the examination in the year gap-o; his eighth son Pil became Military Commander. His daughter married General Shin Myeong-su.

    His son Ju married the daughter of Left Minister Han Myeong-hoe and had three sons: Jong-heup became Magistrate of the Privy Council; Jong-ok became Deputy Official of the Sacrificial Bureau; Jong-ho achieved first place in the civil service examination. His son Myeon married the daughter of Military Official Jung Ho and had two sons and one daughter—the sons were Yong-kwan and Yong-gae, the daughter married Military Official Kang Hak-sun. His son Chan married the daughter of Councilor Yun Jam and had two daughters, one marrying Court Official Jeong Yu-kang, the other marrying Military Officer Hong Tae-sun. His son Jeong married the daughter of the Lord of Houning and had two sons: Yeong-cheol and Yeong-hong, both holding minor offices. His son Jun married the daughter of Cheongju Magistrate Yu Su-chang and had one son, Bok-soon. His son Hyeong married the daughter of General Jeong Bo and had two sons: Kwang-yun and Kwang-taek. His son Pil married the daughter of Kosang Magistrate Yun Sam-won and had three sons and two daughters.

    His grandson Jong-heup married the daughter of the Lord of Papeong and had two sons and two daughters. His grandson Jong-ok married the daughter of Court Official of the Genealogy Bureau and had one son. The sons of Kang Hak-sun were Yeong-su and Hyang-su. He had also one son and one daughter by a concubine—the son was named Gyeol, and the daughter entered the palace.

    The Epitaph:

    Our Great East stands by the sea,
    A realm made splendid by waters.
    Rivers flow and mountains rise high,
    A tapestry woven of breadth and grandeur.
    From the essence of sea and peak,
    Came forth an uncommon man.
    Who was this rare and singular soul?
    A minister whose deeds shook the age.
    With brightness and bold spirit,
    He possessed the vast Haoran breath.
    His measure embraced the cosmos,
    His learning spanned heaven and earth.
    In letters and strategic counsel,
    In military and statecraft wisdom—
    The talents of a kingly advisor.
    All one age he swayed and guided,
    With the ease of a blade through flesh.
    Meeting his time, meeting his sovereign,
    He unfolded his vast designs.
    Quelling inner discord,
    Restoring the great foundation.
    Ordering and assisting transformation,
    He rescued the troubled era.
    Twice he held the nation steady,
    Raising it to luminous peace.
    The kingdom's perilous decline
    Flourished through his efforts.
    All the patterns of governance
    Took their measure from him.
    Going forth as commander,
    Returning to take the helm—
    One body bearing all the nation's fortune.
    His virtue satisfied the people,
    His authority subdued foreign lands.
    Serving through three reigns,
    He accumulated boundless merit.
    With mountains and rivers as witness,
    He received rank and honor.
    His service covered an age,
    His position crowned all officials.
    Long he held the examination seal,
    Yet also managed rite and ceremony.
    With propriety established and music perfected,
    Ghost and man found harmony.
    With teaching spread and custom refined,
    Humanity and righteousness slowly took root.
    Our nation's governance
    Rivaled the Shang and Zhou.
    Our minister's legacy
    Matches Yi Yin and Fu Shuo.

    His virtue, deeply rooted,
    Spreads blessings ever deeper.
    Heaven granted sons in abundance,
    Only a multitude of sons.
    Following the eight dragons of old,
    Brothers who matched each other.
    With numerous worthy grandsons,
    Jade-smooth and pearl-bright,
    Names inscribed in the registers of the examined,
    Starlit steps across the sky.
    Clad in crimson robes and jade insignia,
    The family's glory shines.

    Ah! With sons and grandsons numerous,
    Both worthy and accomplished,
    All from his fragrant virtue
    That reaches to the highest heaven.

    Though the man has passed away,
    His virtue alone endures.
    We inscribe it clear and true—
    Will not posterity take heed?

    Bright across the generations shines his merit,
    Eternally bonding with ancestors.
    We carve this in stone to speak
    To ages yet unborn.
    Those who pass shall weep,
    Remembering his luminous virtue.
  footnotes:
    - 'Hunminjeongeum (언문): The Korean alphabet created by King Sejong in 1443. Shin Sukju played a key role in its formulation and refinement.'
    - 'Wei Zheng (위징): A famous remonstrating minister of the Tang Dynasty known for his honest and fearless counsel to Emperor Taizong. The comparison suggests Shin Sukju similarly provided truthful guidance to Korean rulers.'
    - 'The ''eight dragons'': A reference to the eight worthy sons of Xun Shu of the Eastern Han, used here to praise Shin Sukju''s many capable sons.'
    - 'Yi Yin and Fu Shuo: Legendary sage-ministers of ancient China, models of virtuous service. The comparison elevates Shin Sukju to their level of historical significance.'
